    ],
    "summary": "Long-term thinker approach: repair the chair with durability and future maintainability in mind. Use high-strength materials (epoxy on the crack, polyurethane on the seat) and prefer modular, reversible fasteners (e.g. threaded inserts in place of glued dowels where the joint must be opened). Upgrade weak components — replace the plastic gliders with screw-on oak. The goal is a piece that lasts longer than the original and is easier to service the next time something fails."
  },
  "constraints": {
    "tools_available": "workbench, heat gun, rubber mallet, bar clamps, power drill, drill press, orbital sander, dental pick, syringe, natural bristle brush, Allen key, screwdriver, sandpaper assortment",
    "materials_available": "wood epoxy, oak stock, M6 stainless steel threaded inserts, M6 stainless steel bolts, stainless steel screws, polyurethane varnish, felt cushion, tack cloth",
    "time_budget_minutes": 600,
    "budget_limit": "moderate — quality fasteners and finishes preferred over the cheapest option",
    "skill_level": "advanced",
    "safety_level": "normal",
    "allowed_operations": "disassemble, drill, sand, glue (epoxy), fasten, varnish",
    "avoid_operations": "no irreversible joints where a mechanical alternative is reasonable",
    "additional_constraints": "Where the original joint must be opened for repair, replace it with a serviceable mechanical fastener rather than re-gluing. Document the upgrade so the next intervention is straightforward."
  },
